- prediction intent: check if generative function for variable combinations can generate the original function when combined with other generative functions
- containing intent: 'check that dependent variable is predicted with sub-intent prediction output (identified type variables)'

div.div:
Interface Query Assembly Visual
The intent organization process positions one input format (generative functions) as requiring another input format (type variables), so the type variable conversion is done first and hooked up to the generative function format as an input.
The intent organization process is the process of 'applying an interface' referenced elsewhere, finding the right abstract position of the components of the input, so that their connections & other components can be inferred with the application of consecutive structural layers.
This 'interface query design' process is an application of two problem-solving automation workflows from
https://github.com/outdreamer/build-a-cure/blob/master/docs/workflow/problem_solving_matching.md
:
1. Filter problem definition (Apply structure to Version 1 of query, which is the problem of "how to connect the objects in the input intent task") until it matches solution structure (an interface query that can complete the input intent task (tasks like 'find a relationship between variables' or 'check if these objects act similarly').
2. Apply structure (like using vectorization or systematization) to organize problem objects
Other problem-solving workflows can be used instead of this combination, such as by starting with a conceptual combination that the interface query needs to fulfill & applying structure, or starting from a query structure & removing attributes until it matches, etc.

div.div:
The core interface functions are functions where change develops (new functions tend to develop around these functions).
- find:
- find a structure & components to fill it (build)
- find a sequence of input/output/embedding to integrate components (apply)
- find a structure describing a connection (derive)
- build:
- build a set of filters to apply (find)
- build a combination/integration function (apply)
- build a structure of components matching attributes of a connection (derive)
- apply:
- apply split structures by difference types to make search trivial (find)
- apply combine/integration functions to commponents (build)
- apply filters to component sets (derive)
- derive:
- derive difference types to organize navigation (find)
- derive structure-component matching function (build)
- derive coordinating function chains (apply)
You can see how there are multiple routes given the definitions of the functions. For example, 'organize' can be built with 'apply structure'.

div.div:
Vertex Generative Variable Network
A vertex is a hub variable in a variable network that has multiple important functions/attributes (a variable that is generative/causative/descriptive) - just like the important objects in a system (incentives, efficiencies), the vertexes offer an accurate & effective way to describe a system without losing information while also avoiding listing all information about the system.
The contradictions & other difference types offer a good way to describe a system.
For example, in a network of bias types, generating core difference & combination types, as well as generating other important specific objects like contradictions, would identify the best structure to capture the biases.

div.div:
A solution automation workflow may involve one interface in the interface query, like structure - for example, finding a set of vectors that link the problem & solution when arranged in the right position & direction.
A more complex solution automation workflow may involve multiple interfaces:
- system: standardize to system interface
- change: find highest change variables
- pattern/function: query for patterns & functions that reduce those variables into sub-problems
- problem: solve sub-problems
- structure: aggregate sub-problem solutions into original problem's solution

div.div:
When an input to solve a problem or sub-problem isn't given, the interface query provides direction on how to find/generate that info (check for insights, if none found, check for patterns, if none found check for info-generating functions, etc)
The interface query can also provide the initial solution automation workflow, which is info about how to link structures, as interface queries are info-generating/finding methods.
The solution automation workflow can be a way to find/derive info (an interface query) - such as 'standardize variables to structural interface & match structures until they fit the solution structure' - or the solution automation workflow can involve a specific function with an interface implied (match inputs/outputs of available functions in problem space to get to destination solution).
The difference is that the solution automation workflow starts & ends at the problem interface, meaning it's a specific interface query with that constraint.
The solution automation workflow is also an insight path, leading to a use of information structures that finds information efficiently. So interface queries are also insight paths (if they also fulfill that condition of finding information efficiently).
